Gulf Foreign Ministers Finalize Agenda of Cooperation Council States Summit 

Abu Dhabi 12-5 (AFP) - Gulf Cooperation Council state ministers held in Abu Dhabi today, Saturday, their final preparatory meeting before the Nineteenth Gulf States Summit which will open tomorrow, Monday, in the Emirates' capital.
      
The meeting, which was intended to put the final touches on the summit's agenda,  was attended, besides the foreign ministers of the six Gulf states (Saudi Arabia, the Emirates, Kuwait, Oman, Qatar and Bahrain), by the Council's Secretary-General Jamil Al-Hujailan.
  
The situation in Iraq and the relations with Iran will be the predominant topics of the summit, whose opening session will be attended by the United Nations Secretary-General, Kofi Anan; the League of Arab Nations Secretary-General, Esmat Abdel Majid; the Islamic Conference Organization Secretary-General, Ezzidin Al-Iraqi; and the South African President Nelson Mandela.
     
The summit will discuss the subject of the peace process in the Middle East, security in the Gulf region and bolstering economic cooperation between the Council's states, especially the unification of the customs tariff project.